== Overview == According to the [[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]], in the 19th volume, it was established in [[:en:555 AD|555 AD]] during the reign of [[:en:Emperor Kinmei|Emperor Kinmei]]. The court dispatched [[:en:Soga no Iname|Soga no Iname]], the Ōomi (Great Minister), and Hozumi no Iwayumi Omi to set up the estate in five districts of Kibi Province.<ref>『日本書紀』欽明天皇16年7月4日条</ref>
By [[:en:569 AD|569 AD]], about ten years after the establishment of the {{ill|Tabe|ja|田部|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tabe|qq=}} (administrative farming groups), many individuals of age were avoiding registration in the family registers and evading taxation. As a result, {{ill|Oujin no Toki|ja|王辰爾|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oujin no Toki|qq=}}'s nephew, {{ill|Shirai no Itsu|ja|白猪胆津|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shirai no Itsu|qq=}}, was sent to oversee the Shirai Tabe. He conducted inspections and implemented family registrations for taxation purposes, creating official registers known as "田戸" (Tabe households). For his contributions, Shirai no Itsu was granted the Shirai surname and the kabane (hereditary title) of {{ill|Fuhito|ja|史|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fuhito|qq=}} (scribe).<ref>『日本書紀』欽明天皇30th year 1月1日条</ref>
In the reign of [[Emperor Bidatsu]], around [[:en:574 AD|574 AD]], the Ōomi [[:en:Soga no Umako|Soga no Umako]] increased the scope of Shirai no Miyake and its Tabe workers, granting the official family registers of Shirai to Shirai no Itsu.<ref>『日本書紀』敏達天皇3rd year 10月9日条</ref>
== Historical Verification == There are several theories about the location of Shirai no Miyake: 1. Ōba District (modern-day Maniwa City, Okayama Prefecture) 2. Mountainous areas in northern Kibi Province 3. Overlap with {{ill|Kojima no Miyake|ja|児島屯倉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojima no Miyake|qq=}}
The most prominent theory links it to the Gotan temple ruins in Maniwa City, formerly part of the ancient Ōba District. This is supported by records in the [[:en:Shoku Nihongi|Shoku Nihongi]], which mention figures such as Shirai no Omi Ōtari and Shirai no Omi Akito, associated with Ōba District.<ref>『続日本紀』天平神護2nd year 12月29日条、神護景雲2nd year 5月3日条</ref>
Artifacts from the Gotan temple site, such as roof tiles resembling those of [[Goguryeo]], and the location's proximity to the strategic [[Izumo Kaidō]], reinforce the connection between Shirai no Miyake and ancient Yamato governance.
== Regional and Political Context == Shirai no Miyake, along with Kojima no Miyake, was strategically placed to isolate and weaken the power of the Kibi ruling authority, a measure intensified during the reigns of [[Emperor Yūryaku]] and [[:en:Emperor Keitai|Emperor Keitai]]. It reflects the Yamato court's evolving governance practices, possibly influenced by [[Northern Wei]]'s [[:en:Equal-field system|Equal-field system]], transmitted via [[:en:Goguryeo|Goguryeo]].<ref>『日本書紀』欽明天皇31st year 4月2日条</ref>
